{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:40","names":{"en":"Carmathian","tr":"Karmatîler (Ebû Saîdî kolu)","ar":"al-Qarāmita (Āl Abī Sa'īd al-Jannābī)"},"country":["BH","IQ","IR","OM","SA","SY"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1078},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"40","atlas_name_en_original":"The Carmathian or Qarmati Rulers of the line of Abū Sa'īd al-Jannābī","parent_tribe":"İsmâilî mezhep hareketi","ethnic_origin":"Arap (çeşitli)","capital":"al-Ahsā (Lahsā)","region_primary":"Doğu Arabistan (al-Ahsā / Bahreyn)","regions_all":"al-Ahsā; Bahreyn; Güney Irak (geçici); Suriye sınırı (geçici); Umân (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":null,"successor":"Uyûnîler (Banū Murra)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Qarmatians represented the most radical branch of Ismaili Shiism, a militant movement that shook the Islamic world by stealing the Black Stone from the Kaaba. Their egalitarian community model established in eastern Arabia, while controversial, constituted one of the most provocative experiments in Islamic political thought.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"25.38","capital_lon":"49.59","century_start":9,"century_end":11}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:54","names":{"en":"Āl Bū Sa'īd","tr":"Âl Bû Saîd","ar":"Āl Bū Sa'īd"},"country":["BH","IR","OM","SA"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"54","atlas_name_en_original":"The Āl Bū Sa'īd","parent_tribe":"İbâdî aile","ethnic_origin":"Arap","capital":"Maskat (Muscat); Zengibar (Sa'îd b. Sultān)","region_primary":"Umân (Maskat) ve Zengibar","regions_all":"Umân; Maskat; Zengibar; Doğu Afrika kıyıları; Bahreyn (geçici); Bender Abbas (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Ya'rubîler","successor":"(devam ediyor — Umân Sultanlığı)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Al Bu Said have governed Oman from the 18th century to the present, establishing a powerful maritime trade empire in Zanzibar. Under Sultan Qaboos (1970-2020), a modern state was built with oil revenues.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"23.61","capital_lon":"58.54","century_start":null,"century_end":null}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:166","names":{"en":"Sultans of Ma'bar","tr":"Ma'bar (Madura) Sultanları","ar":"Salātīn Ma'bar"},"country":["IN","OM"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"166","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sultans of Ma'bar or Madura","parent_tribe":"Delhi Sultanlığı valileri","ethnic_origin":"Türk/Hindistanlı","capital":"Madura","region_primary":"Güney Hindistan (Ma'bar / Madura)","regions_all":"Madura; Koromantel kıyısı","geographic_zone":"Güney Asya","predecessor":"Delhi Tuğluklu valileri","successor":"Vijayanagar fethi","government_type":"Sultanlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sultans of Ma'bar represented a short-lived Islamic rule in southern India centered on Madura. Established when Delhi Tughluq governors gained independence, the sultanate was destroyed by the Vijayanagara Hindu Empire.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"9.92","capital_lon":"78.12","century_start":14,"century_end":14}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:75","names":{"en":"Būyid","tr":"Büveyhîler (Bûyîler)","ar":"al-Būyahiyyūn / al-Buwayhiyyūn"},"country":["IQ","IR","OM"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":932,"extinct":1062},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"75","atlas_name_en_original":"The Būyids or Buwayhids","parent_tribe":"Bûye ailesi (Deylemi)","ethnic_origin":"İranî (Deylemi)","capital":"Şîraz (Fars); Bağdat (Irak); Rey (Cibâl)","region_primary":"Irak, Fars, Cibâl, Kirmân","regions_all":"Bağdat/Irak; Fars (Şîraz); Cibâl (Rey, Hemedân, İsfahan); Kirmân; Hûzistân; Umân (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Irak/Cezîre","predecessor":"Abbâsî doğrudan yönetimi (Irak); Sâcîler/Müsâfirîler (Fars)","successor":"Selçuklular (tüm kollar)","government_type":"Hilafet","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Būyids represent the most paradoxical dynasty in Islamic history, emerging from the Daylam mountains on the Caspian coast to conquer Baghdad and directly control the Abbasid caliph. Rather than destroying the Sunni caliphate, this Shī'ī military power pragmatically utilized it as a legitimacy instrument, creating a unique model in Islamic political tradition. Governing in five branches across Fars, Iraq, Jibal, and Kirman, they maintained dominance for over a century. Transplanting the Daylamī military tradition to the heart of the Islamic world, they also played a pioneering role in literary and scientific patronage.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"33.31","capital_lon":"44.37","century_start":10,"century_end":11}}
